      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I didn't know whether to laugh or cry after reading ''The Biologist and the Sea: Lessons in Marine-Life Restoration'' (Oct. 24). The combination of arrogance and ignorance displayed is totally phenomenal.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I didn't know whether to laugh or cry after reading ''The Biologist and the Sea: Lessons in Marine-Life Restoration'' (Oct. 24). The combination of arrogance and ignorance displayed is totally phenomenal.</p>
        <p>We inhabitants of this finite earth face unprecedented horrors associated with six-billion-plus humans and their antinatural lifestyles. With global warming in full cry, we don't recreate by burning fossil fuels in boat motors. We don't catch a beautiful sea creature ''prized for both its fight and its flavor'' because the act makes us feel relaxed or rejuvenated. We don't express our love of nature by creating toxic smoke and underwater noise.</p>
        <p>What we do to recreate is walk or swim or bike gently, leaving no trace of our passing. We respect the nature of Nature. We have a tiny window in which to relearn the meaning of ''recreation.''</p>
        <p>Kirk S. Nevin  Corvallis, Ore.</p>
      </block>
